00:00:26.685 --> 00:00:29.480
JOE HADZIMA: OK, Good evening.

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:32.670
Everybody nice and
warm from the snow?

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:35.490
Thank you for coming to Nuts
and Bolts of New Ventures

00:00:35.490 --> 00:00:39.860
and Business Plans on a
snowy night in Cambridge.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:41.320
My name is Joe Hadzima.

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:44.090
And this is the first
of six evenings we're

00:00:44.090 --> 00:00:46.350
going to have for the course.

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:49.950
The course name is Nuts
and Bolts of New Ventures

00:00:49.950 --> 00:00:51.250
and Business Plans.

00:00:51.250 --> 00:00:55.700
First of all, it's not really
about the business plan itself.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:58.140
Think of it as we're going
to talk about how to plan

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:01.870
and execute a new venture.

00:01:01.870 --> 00:01:04.150
And don't think
of a business plan

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:08.030
as a fixed document
in this course.

00:01:08.030 --> 00:01:11.410
Really, it's a dynamic
process we're going through.

00:01:11.410 --> 00:01:13.150
It may be a document.

00:01:13.150 --> 00:01:15.774
It may be a few slides.

00:01:15.774 --> 00:01:17.190
But at the end of
the day, what it

00:01:17.190 --> 00:01:21.420
ends up being is a
shared vision between you

00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:26.060
and your team as to where
we are, where we're going,

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:28.780
and how we plan to get there.

00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:32.370
So that's the goal of all this.

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:34.820
And I should also
say, because I know

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:37.700
some people in the audience are
not doing traditional business

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:42.340
ventures, we're going to use
the business terms a lot,

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:45.580
but this could equally apply
to social-developmental

00:01:45.580 --> 00:01:50.610
entrepreneurship, to nonprofits
even to governmental ventures.

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:54.130
It's a way of thinking about
how to organize new ideas

00:01:54.130 --> 00:01:56.480
and get them going.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:58.410
Now a little bit
about the course.

00:01:58.410 --> 00:02:00.430
This is the 25th
year-- it's hard for me

00:02:00.430 --> 00:02:03.660
to believe it's been 25
years-- for the course.

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:06.950
And the founding of the course
has an entrepreneurial lesson

00:02:06.950 --> 00:02:08.060
in it.

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:09.590
So here's the backstory.

00:02:09.590 --> 00:02:13.180
I was teaching some things
here on legal stuff.

00:02:13.180 --> 00:02:17.110
And some students
came up and said--

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:18.970
I think we had one
entrepreneurship

00:02:18.970 --> 00:02:20.485
course at Sloan at
the time and they

00:02:20.485 --> 00:02:22.850
had taken that-- and they
said it's a great course,

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:27.110
but it's not telling
us anything practical.

00:02:27.110 --> 00:02:30.050
So could you do a
course during IAP

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:32.470
to tell us how to do
something practical,

00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:34.460
how to start a company?

00:02:34.460 --> 00:02:38.740
So this was back 25 years
ago before the internet.

00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:42.580
And the IAP courses were
in a fixed, printed catalog

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:43.480
that you would get.

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:45.260
Shows you how far we've come.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.950
So I said, well, I'll
think about doing a course

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:49.290
and let me get back to you.

00:02:49.290 --> 00:02:52.650
Well, I got tied-up
with some other things.

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:56.110
And then they came to me and
said, we put it in the catalog

00:02:56.110 --> 00:03:00.010
and we dare you not to show up.

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:01.220
Interesting.

00:03:01.220 --> 00:03:03.160
So I thought about
it for a while

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:04.860
and I thought, well,
I should be angry,

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:08.110
but I think I have a customer.

00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:09.820
I think these people
want something.

00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:12.285
So the first attribute
was I had a customer.

00:03:12.285 --> 00:03:14.450
I'll right, I'll play
this game for a bit.

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:17.970
Problem is I only had
two weeks to organize it.

00:03:17.970 --> 00:03:20.780
So that wasn't enough time
to really do anything formal.

00:03:20.780 --> 00:03:25.870
So I said-- I think it was
four nights-- all right,

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:29.580
we'll do two hours, three
hours, we'll do eight topics

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.932
and I'll go and find some
people who know about those.

00:03:32.932 --> 00:03:35.140
And how am I going to make
it easy at the last minute

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:36.430
to get these people?

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:39.320
I said just come into class
and whatever the field

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:43.515
is that you're in speak maybe
10 minutes on the five things

00:03:43.515 --> 00:03:45.890
I wish somebody had told me
about whatever you're talking

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:47.760
about before I got started.

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:50.615
Then we'll do
questions and answers.

00:03:50.615 --> 00:03:52.490
And I said, I've got to
make it entertaining.

00:03:52.490 --> 00:03:55.800
So I called up people
and said, do you

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.960
know somebody who
can do this talk?

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:01.625
And if you do, you have to
have seen the person talk,

00:04:01.625 --> 00:04:05.100
they have to be entertaining,
you have to vouch for them.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:08.500
And so we did this in
a period of two weeks.

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:10.540
And probably half
the speakers that

00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:13.870
showed up for that first
session I had never met before.

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:17.730
So I'm thinking this is
going to be a disaster.

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:19.709
It turned out to
be a great success.

00:04:19.709 --> 00:04:22.590
And I think the
lessons for this,

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:28.280
in an entrepreneurial way were
I had a customer for a product,

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:32.570
they wanted something, I
was able to clearly define

00:04:32.570 --> 00:04:35.580
the task-- because I didn't
have time to do anything more;

00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:37.310
if I had done it
myself, it probably

00:04:37.310 --> 00:04:38.810
would have taken
longer and not been

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:44.110
as good-- I got great people,
and I was able to communicate

00:04:44.110 --> 00:04:49.480
to them what the task was, and
then I got out of their way

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:50.600
and they did a great job.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:52.180
So there's an
entrepreneurial lesson

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:53.830
in how to start a company.

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:57.590
Make sure you have
customers, get great people.

00:04:57.590 --> 00:05:00.350
The whole business planning,
new venture-type thing

00:05:00.350 --> 00:05:03.080
is really trying to
find what the task is

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:05.580
and then to be able to
communicate, and execute on it.

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:09.214
So the course really is
an entrepreneur venture.

00:05:09.214 --> 00:05:10.130
That's how we started.

00:05:10.130 --> 00:05:14.539
And later Joost
basically figured out

00:05:14.539 --> 00:05:15.830
how we could get credit for it.

00:05:15.830 --> 00:05:18.450
And it's just
blossomed ever since.

00:05:18.450 --> 00:05:21.820
So that's the background.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:25.490
In the 25 years we've
seen all sorts of things.

00:05:25.490 --> 00:05:29.610
We've seen bubbles--
the internet bubble.

00:05:29.610 --> 00:05:32.750
I stood here thinking I
just read in the paper

00:05:32.750 --> 00:05:36.810
that Hotmail, back
in 1997 or so,

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:44.450
had started up and been sold
in 18 months for $450 million,

00:05:44.450 --> 00:05:45.730
basically giving away email.

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:47.480
And I'm thinking how
am I going to explain

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:49.440
to people this isn't
the way it usually

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:51.950
works in periods of time.

00:05:51.950 --> 00:05:53.270
More recently, Instagram.

00:05:53.270 --> 00:05:57.090
So there are some things that
happen at points in time that

00:05:57.090 --> 00:05:59.730
defy direct logic.

00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:01.970
And if you can
catch those waves,

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:05.390
that becomes a good thing to do.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:08.170
We've also seen busts after
the internet collapsed,

00:06:08.170 --> 00:06:10.840
after the financial
markets collapsed.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:15.270
Actually, that is one of the
best times to start a company.

00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:17.320
And many of the really
enduring companies

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:19.770
have been started
during down times.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.850
And the reason is resources
aren't available-- financing

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:26.070
dries up-- you've got
to be really focused,

00:06:26.070 --> 00:06:28.350
you have to actually
deliver something of value.

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:31.260
And there's a lot of history
about companies to get

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:33.400
started during down times.

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:36.930
But through all of
that, ups and downs,

00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:39.240
it all boils down to
really two basic thoughts,

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:41.390
and we're going to touch
on it over and over again

00:06:41.390 --> 00:06:43.190
in the course.

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:46.600
And that is whether it's
a business, whether it's

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:51.360
a nonprofit, whether it's
a governmental project,

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:54.470
the first thing you've
got to do is create value.

00:06:54.470 --> 00:06:58.479
So if you're not creating value,
You can't really do anything.

00:06:58.479 --> 00:07:00.270
And then having created
value, the question

00:07:00.270 --> 00:07:03.810
is how do you capture
some or all of that value

00:07:03.810 --> 00:07:06.580
to make what you're
doing sustainable.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:13.740
And sustainable in the concept
of the traditional companies is

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:17.350
profit and in the context
of developmental stuff

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:20.760
it can be we can do it
again, rinse and repeat.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:22.494
So when we look
at creating value,

00:07:22.494 --> 00:07:23.910
we're going to be
asking questions

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:27.140
about who do we
create value for,

00:07:27.140 --> 00:07:33.340
how much value do we create,
and how do we create it.

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:35.290
And then when we talk
about capturing value,

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:40.570
the traditional way has been
for customers somebody who

00:07:40.570 --> 00:07:44.830
will pay you for your
goods, the product you do,

00:07:44.830 --> 00:07:46.220
or your services.

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:48.910
And the trick, as we'll see,
in financial projections

00:07:48.910 --> 00:07:50.420
and the business
model parts that'll

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:54.710
come in the next few days, is
that whole process something

00:07:54.710 --> 00:07:57.920
where you can make enough
money that you can continue it.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:02.230
So traditional capture of
value is through customers.

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:04.750
There are other ways
to capture value

00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:09.320
in the area of the
advertising or monetization

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:11.660
that we'll talk about also.

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:15.930
And you think about things like
where third parties provide

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:17.470
that payment.

00:08:17.470 --> 00:08:19.110
So think of the US
health care system

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:23.280
where historically the patient,
the person who the value is

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:26.650
delivered to-- as in you're
going to get treated--

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:29.800
isn't really paying
directly the cost of that.

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:31.770
So sometimes figuring
out how that works

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:33.320
can be the challenging part.

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:43.640
So at the end of the day,
to make all this happy,

00:08:43.640 --> 00:08:46.390
we're going to need people--
that's the number one

00:08:46.390 --> 00:08:48.200
thing you're going to
need for a venture--

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:53.822
resources of some sort-- either
cash or partnerships-- skills--

00:08:53.822 --> 00:08:56.030
some of them you'll learn
in this class, some of them

00:08:56.030 --> 00:08:59.000
you'll learn on the job--
and then that one that's

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.800
the hardest one to figure
out, but if you can get it

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:04.200
it's the best, and
that's called luck.

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:07.440
I'll always, go with some luck.

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:11.000
So our goal for the
course is basically

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.740
to make sure you get infected
with the entrepreneurial

00:09:15.740 --> 00:09:17.490
thinking virus.

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:22.540
And it really is a virus
that can be infectious.

00:09:22.540 --> 00:09:26.430
The good news is it's
not known to be fatal.

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:27.980
It's highly contagious.

00:09:27.980 --> 00:09:32.850
It is a lifelong affliction, so
you'll have to get used to it.

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:35.260
But at the end of the day,
I think if you catch it

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:36.850
you'll be in best shape.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:41.670
This is what we're going
to be doing tonight.

00:09:41.670 --> 00:09:44.660
We're going to tell you a little
bit about who you are, we're

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:47.390
going to introduce
the teaching team,

00:09:47.390 --> 00:09:50.230
we'll introduce the case
study and business plan

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:53.920
basics tonight, and then
we'll take a small break,

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:55.980
and then we'll get on
with Steve Pearse, who's

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:58.850
come all the way from
Florida today to talk to us.

00:09:58.850 --> 00:10:04.570
He's thinking maybe that
wasn't such a good idea.

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:05.665
So who is in the class?

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:14.140
Some of you signed up-- many of
you signed up-- at the website.

00:10:14.140 --> 00:10:15.690
We had 160 signed up.

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:18.114
And the organizations
that you're from

00:10:18.114 --> 00:10:20.030
are-- and I'll just read
them alphabetically--

00:10:20.030 --> 00:10:24.740
Boston University, Broad
Institute, Columbia University,

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:28.030
the Department of Defense,
Harvard College, Harvard

00:10:28.030 --> 00:10:30.730
Kennedy School, and
Harvard Business School,

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:34.400
Mass General Hospital,
University of Massachusetts,

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:38.620
University of Macedonia,
University of Michigan,

00:10:38.620 --> 00:10:41.745
Toronto, Wellesley College,
several private companies

00:10:41.745 --> 00:10:46.610
that I won't say your names to
protect you, and of course MIT.

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:48.710
Now the areas that you
said you were interested

00:10:48.710 --> 00:10:50.200
in are all over the place.

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:54.500
We have consumer devices,
foreign language learning,

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:57.580
financial technology,
social enterprise

00:10:57.580 --> 00:11:01.880
related to health care,
educational technology,

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:02.772
medical devices.

