We have nuclear energy--
for those of you

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:22.910
into that-- specialty biotech
chemicals, a sleep product,

00:11:22.910 --> 00:11:28.970
oncology drug delivery,
biotechnology, 3D printing,

00:11:28.970 --> 00:11:34.500
eyeglasses in West Africa,
independent film industry, lab

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:40.490
testing process and equipment,
big data, data privacy,

00:11:40.490 --> 00:11:46.040
B2B information technology,
energy technology, aerospace,

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:49.050
crowd-funding, and e-commerce.

00:11:49.050 --> 00:11:52.590
So hopefully you'll find
a kindred spirit in those.

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:55.230
Now what about the
background of the people?

00:11:55.230 --> 00:11:59.050
We have some people this is
the first course they've ever

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:01.674
taken in entrepreneurship.

00:12:01.674 --> 00:12:03.340
We've had people that
have taken a bunch

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:05.340
of other entrepreneurial
courses at MIT

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:07.347
or at other universities.

00:12:07.347 --> 00:12:09.180
In fact, we have a
couple of people who have

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:12.030
taken Nuts and Bolts before.

00:12:12.030 --> 00:12:15.520
They did pass before, but
they're back for more.

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:19.520
Several start-ups, somebody who
has always been in government,

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:25.530
and a couple people in 15 plus
years in large organizations.

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:28.070
And some members of the
venture mentoring service

00:12:28.070 --> 00:12:30.520
are actually in the audience.

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:33.240
So we have undergraduates,
grad students, post-docs,

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:35.450
visiting faculty, and staff.

00:12:35.450 --> 00:12:39.510
So it's a pretty
diverse audience

00:12:39.510 --> 00:12:40.760
and we've got a lot to cover.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:43.530
So a little advice to the
people that are first timers.

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:46.580
I would say soak it all in.

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:48.829
And as you go
forward, try to think

00:12:48.829 --> 00:12:50.620
about the kind of things
we talk about when

00:12:50.620 --> 00:12:54.660
you approach entrepreneurial
things for the first time.

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:58.670
More experienced people, now use
this to refine your thinking.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:01.950
I've been in this course
for, as I said, 25 years.

00:13:01.950 --> 00:13:04.540
And every single year I
come up with some refinement

00:13:04.540 --> 00:13:07.220
of my thinking listening
not only the speakers

00:13:07.220 --> 00:13:09.770
but to the questions that come.

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:13.380
So I hope you enjoy the course.

00:13:13.380 --> 00:13:19.246
We do have to calibrate
before we get going, though.

00:13:19.246 --> 00:13:23.310
It is MIT, so we have
our first formula.

00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:32.270
And it is H equals
R divided by E.

00:13:32.270 --> 00:13:35.480
So I've got an audience with a
whole bunch of different people

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:38.670
and we're trying to
solve this equation.

00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:41.844
And we're trying
to maximize H. So

00:13:41.844 --> 00:13:43.260
for those of you
that can't see, H

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:46.970
equals R divided by E.
Anybody want to take

00:13:46.970 --> 00:13:49.410
a guess what these symbols are?

00:13:52.805 --> 00:13:54.426
Yeah, the snow has got to you.

